# The value of `i`

After this loop:

    for (i = len - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--)
        //...

the value of `i` is -1, given that `len` is greater or equal to 0.

The loop repeats as long as its condition is met. The condition is `i &gt;= 0`. When `i` is decremented to 0 the condition is still met and the loop runs another time. At the end `i--` is executed and `i` becomes -1. Now the condition evaluates to `false` and the loop breaks.

If you now execute

    RevStr[i] = &#39;\0&#39;;

the character **before** `RevStr` will be overwritten. This is an out-of-bounds access that might destroy any other thing. Behaviour is undefined now, anything can happen, from &quot;nothing&quot; to &quot;the world implodes, at least for the program.&quot;

# Where to store &#39;\0&#39;

A string is commonly limited in C by the special character &#39;\0&#39;. It belongs to the end of the string.

After the loop `j` indexes the character **after** the last copied character in `RevStr`. So you can write this to mark the end of the string:

    RevStr[j] = &#39;\0&#39;;

The reason why `j` has that value is left as an exercise for you. You might like to insert some `printf()` at strategic places to watch variables, or to learn to use a debugger.

# The formatted output

*Note: I&#39;d like to recommend to read your C lectures once more. Or, in lack of such, look up the description of `printf()`. You should get used to this because you will never learn all details of any programming language. Actually I&#39;m &quot;doing C&quot; since more than 30 years for a life and I still look up details just to make sure I do it right.*

    printf(&quot;\n String after Reversing = %s&quot;, RevStr);

But for your convenience, here is a short explanation. The first argument to `printf()` is a format string. As long as no &#39;%&#39; is encountered every character is output as given. Now if a &#39;%&#39; is found the next character(s) decide how to proceed. In this case the next character is &#39;s&#39; which means that the next argument is interpreted as a pointer to a string that will be output. So after the blank after the &#39;=&#39; the contents of `RevStr` is output. That&#39;s why it is so important that the string is limited by &#39;\0&#39;.

